Data Entry and Cleaning

Importing the data from an excel sheet on my desktop with all of the siliques

#data from desktop
Sildata <- read.csv("/Users/jackhoward/Desktop/Switch Tracking - Silique_Data.csv", header = TRUE)

#tidying up to get group and replicate
Sildata <-
  Sildata %>%
  separate(Silique_ID, c("Group", "Replicate"), sep = "[S]") %>%
  rename(Seed_Density = present.length) %>%
  filter(Bilateral == "Y")

Sildata$Genotype = substr(Sildata$Group, 1, 1)
Sildata$Switch = substring(Sildata$Group, 2)
Sildata$Replicate <- gsub("_", replacement = "", Sildata$Replicate)

Overarching Plot

Sildata %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Group, y = Seed_Density)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1))

ANOVA Data Validation

Chose this analysis to simultaneously evaluate the affect of two grouping variables (genotype and switching) on one response variable (seed density). There are two assumptions to ANOVA

  1. Residuals are normally distributed
# creating the anova analysis using type 1
anova <-lm(Seed_Density~Genotype*Switch, data=Sildata)
res.aov <- aov(Seed_Density~Genotype*Switch, data=Sildata)

# plot 1: distribution
plot(density(anova$residuals))

# plot 2: Q-Q plot
plot(res.aov, 2)

Distribution displays as roughly normal. Q-Q plot has downturn at the ends but is fair to the line.

  1. There is equal variance among groups
plot(res.aov, 1)

# plot(anova$residuals~anova$fitted.values)
# from the original guide but doesn't have the fitted line in the middle

Fine straight line with some low outlier residuals.

ANOVA Values

anova(res.aov)

Tukey Test for Significance

As the ANOVA test is significant, we can compute Tukey HSD (Tukey Honest Significant Differences) for performing multiple pairwise-comparison between the means of groups

# Running the function using the anova as an input
Tuk_table <- TukeyHSD(res.aov, which = "Genotype:Switch")

Tuk_table <- as.data.frame(Tuk_table$"Genotype:Switch")
colnames(Tuk_table) <- c("diff", "lwr", "upr", "pvalue")

# filtering for only the combinations that have a significant p value
Tuk_table <-
  Tuk_table %>%
  filter(pvalue < 0.05) 

Tuk_table <- tibble::rownames_to_column(Tuk_table, "Code")

# filtering for combinations in the same genotype or same switch
Tuk_table <-
  Tuk_table %>%
  separate(Code, c("C1", "C2"), sep = "-") %>%
  separate(C1, c("C1-Geno", "C1-Switch"), sep = ":") %>%
  separate(C2, c("C2-Geno", "C2-Switch"), sep = ":") %>%
  filter(`C1-Geno` == `C2-Geno` | `C1-Switch` == `C2-Switch`)

head(Tuk_table, 10)

Genotype Plots

Wild Type

WT <-
  Sildata %>%
  filter(grepl("^C", Group))

# wild type comparisons from Tukey table

WT_comp <- list( c("C16_C", "C12_F2"), c("C12_F1", "C12_C"), c("C12_F2", "C12_C"),
                 c("C12_F3", "C12_C"), c("C12_F4", "C12_C"), c("C16_B", "C12_C"))
                 
WT %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Group, y = Seed_Density)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.1, size = 1) +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  ggtitle("Wild Type Siliques") +
  ylab("Seed Density (Present/Length (mm)") +
  stat_compare_means(comparisons = WT_comp)
